STATISTICAL MODELLING OF QUALITY OF LIFE MEASUREMENT

logo France

                              calanque, Luminy
   The international conference will take place at the Faculty of Science
          of Marseille, Luminy (Amphi 12) on September 12-13, 2013

   The seminar concerns statistical analysis of quality of life obtained
   from patients with chronic diseases.
   The "quality of life" being non observable, is generally quantified by
   means of the responses to standardized questionnaires completed by the
   subjects. Questionnaires contain tens of items classified by the
   quality of life dimensions they should measure. Such data arise with
   several problems such as the selection of informative and non redondant
   items, missing data, comparing differents questionnaires results,
   modeling the score computed from the items, modelling the trend of such
   scores through longitudinal studies.
   This seminar will put together scientists coming from different
   disciplins: mathematics, health, epidemiology, psychology,...It aims to
   present through talks given by experts the state of the art of the main
   problems arising from QoL data measurements. Mathematicians will give
   insight in the methodological developments in this area.

   Three topics are covered in this seminar:

     * The missing data treatment.
     * Items selection, item banking and Computerized Adaptive Testing.
     * Modeling the Response Shift.

   Two teams are associated in the organization of this meeting: the
   statistics team of the Mathematical Institute of Luminy (FRE3529) and
   the Research Unit "Public Health, Quality of Life and Chronic Diseases"
   (EA3279), Faculty of medicine La Timone, together with the National
   Platform Quality of Life and Cancer. Other teams and researchers coming
   from France and abroad from various disciplines contribute also to the
   event.

   The meeting is sponsored by the National Platform Quality of Life, the
   merging team CUD QV IReSP, Aix Marseille University and the French
   Statistical Society.

   Target audience: statisticians, biostatisticians, epidemiologists,
   public health physicians, resarechers engineers and PhD students.

   Expected audience: Approximately 100 participants.

